<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-395-232  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 395 232.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  April 23 1990 v7 n17 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC fills in details of plan to reduce ATandamp;T regulation: sayscurrent structure may be harmful to users. (Federal CommunicationsCommission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FCC publishes a report on its decision to lessen regulation ofATandamp;T.andP;  Proposed changes would allow ATandamp;T to offer discounted andcustom network deals through non-tariffed arrangements and privatedeals.andP;  The streamlining of the tariffing procedure for certainATandamp;T business services is also recommended.andP;  According to the FCC,the long-distance industry is competitive enough to allow alifting of the constraints placed on ATandamp;T.andP;  Competitors, however,argue that ATandamp;T still has between 66- to 69 percent of theinterstate market.andP;  The FCC agrees that ATandamp;T has the largest sharebut it also concludes that regulation should not be based totallyon market share; the FCC's analysis relied on competitors'facilities and their ability to meet user demands.andP;  The FCC isconfident that it can halt any attempt by ATandamp;T to create predatorypricing.andP;  Parties have until Jun 12, 1990 to file comments.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationProposalCommunications Service SuppliersUser NeedsCompetitionCommunications Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>